        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1950-05-23T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1950-05-23T00:00:00-05:00" n="78"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d78">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">700.00/5–1650</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum by the Chief of the Program Staff, Mutual Defense
                        Assistance Program</hi> (<hi rend="italic">Bray</hi>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">top secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1950-05-23">May 23,
                            1950</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p rend="flushleft">Memorandum for the 8.04 File</p>
                <p rend="flushleft">Subject: Base Requirements in <gloss target="#t_NAT1"
                        >NAT</gloss> Defense Plans</p>
                <p rend="flushleft">Source: TSS May 16, 1950.<note n="1" xml:id="d78fn1">Top secret
                        summary <gloss target="#t_Telac1">Telac</gloss> 12 (telegram 12 to Acheson
                        at London), not printed; 700.00/5–1650.</note>
                </p>
                <p>In referring to the NCS [<gloss target="#t_JCS1">
                        <hi rend="italic">JCS</hi>
                    </gloss>] our recent letter concerning defense facilities in Greenland and the
                    general question of base rights within the North Atlantic Treaty area,<note
                        n="2" xml:id="d78fn2">Not found in Department of State files.</note> the
                    Secretary of Defense expressed concurrence with our view that in many instances
                    the acquisition of <pb facs="0146" n="126" xml:id="pg_126"/> facilities and
                    privileges in <gloss target="#t_NAT1">NAT</gloss> countries will depend upon the
                    completion of agreed <gloss target="#t_NATO1">NATO</gloss> plans setting forth
                    the requirements from a military viewpoint for such facilities or operating
                    arrangements. Accordingly, Secretary Johnson requested the <gloss
                        target="#t_JCS1">JCS</gloss> to take the necessary action to insure that the
                        <gloss target="#t_NAT1">NAT</gloss> regional defense plans adequately
                    reflect ITS requirements for military rights. He further asked that, when agreed
                        <gloss target="#t_NATO1">NATO</gloss> plans have proceeded to a point
                    justifying a “bilateral approach to the country concerned, he be informed in
                    order that final arrangements may be concluded by direct negotiation. This
                    procedure, he stated, should not delay or otherwise alter negotiations now
                    proceeding satisfactorily or those which lie outside the <gloss target="#t_NAT1"
                        >NAT</gloss> area.</p>
            </div>
